{"id":"1602.01501","submitter":"Stefania Ottaviano","authors":"Stefano Bonaccorsi and Stefania Ottaviano","title":"Epidemics on networks with heterogeneous population and stochastic\n  infection rates","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Mathematical Biosciences (2016), pp. 43-52","doi":"10.1016/j.mbs.2016.07.002","report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper we study the diffusion of an SIS-type epidemics on a network\nunder the presence of a random environment, that enters in the definition of\nthe infection rates of the nodes. Accordingly, we model the infection rates in\nthe form of independent stochastic processes. To analyze the problem, we apply\na mean field approximation, which allows to get a stochastic differential\nequations for the probability of infection in each node, and classical tools\nabout stability, which require to find suitable Lyapunov's functions. Here, we\nfind conditions which guarantee, respectively, extinction and stochastic\npersistence of the epidemics. We show that there exists two regions, given in\nterms of the coefficients of the model, one where the system goes to extinction\nalmost surely, and the other where it is stochastic permanent. These two\nregions are, unfortunately, not adjacent, as there is a gap between them, whose\nextension depends on the specific level of noise. In this last region, we\nperform numerical analysis to suggest the true behavior of the solution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Feb 2016 22:34:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 1 Mar 2016 11:00:34 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 21 Jul 2016 20:15:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-07-25"}
