{"id":"1602.01561","submitter":"Penying Rochanakul","authors":"Penying Rochanakul","title":"$k$-geometric graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A finite, simple and undirected graph $G = (V, E)$ with $p$ vertices and $q$\nedges is said to be a $k$-geometric mean graph for a positive integer $k$ if\nthere is an injection $\\psi :V(G)\\to \\{k,k+1,\\dots,k+q\\}$ such that, when each\nedge $uv\\in E(G)$ is assigned the label $\\lfloor\\sqrt{\\psi(u)\\psi(v)}\\rfloor$\nor $\\lceil\\sqrt{\\psi(u)\\psi(v)}\\rceil$, the resulting edge label set is\n$\\{k,k+1,...,k+q-1\\}$ and $\\psi$ is called a \\emph{$k$-geometric mean labeling}\nof $G$. The special case $k=1$, a $1$-geometric mean labeling is called a\ngeometric mean labeling, and a $1$-geometric mean graph is called a geometric\nmean graph.\n  In this paper, we present new classes of geometric mean graphs. Then we\nintroduce $k$-geometric mean labeling and prove some classes of graphs are\n$k$-geometric mean. We also study some classes of finite join of graphs that\nadmit geometric mean labeling.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Feb 2016 05:45:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-02-05"}
